<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100666328141721></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100666328141721><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=5410&mid=100666328141721>Cleric Tactics</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=5410&mid=100666328141721#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=97392><span id= >mjvecellio</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>2 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sat, Nov 24th 11:41 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>   Just a few extra thoughts to add to the already helpful tips and strategies posted by Dryten & Changling.  First and Foremost, talk to your group mates!  I play in lots of so-called "pick-up" groups as I am an occasional player and as a cleric, knowing group dynamics is a must.  Not everyone plays their class the same and the little things can bite you in the end, if you are not careful..  Small things can eliminate down time, such as melee classess using the bind wound skill and monks having mend available for an emergency heal.  Another thing is asking your main tank and main puller how many hps they have ( after buffs, of course) so you know exactly how many heals its gonna take  to keep them alive if the situation goes south.  I especially concur with the consensus of keeping the enchanter alive in a group and  I even have a hot key designed so that if our chanter gets  beat upon,  all it takes is one keystroke to keep  him/her alive.  Also, get used to using your F keys to target group members as opposed to using your mouse, it is much quicker and accurate, thereby saving time, and perhaps, your party.  <br>     I must disagree with some of the previous posters however on the use of root.  I find it is resisted and broken way too often to be of help and the agro it generates, ( on top of whatever healing you have been doing) to be not worth its casting.  I have found much more success with the stun line of spells.  I have found even my level 9 (?) stun spell to be just as effective as my midlevel stuns with resists typically only occuring with high yellow or red mobs.  Evens and blues rarely resist and it uses so little mana that it becomes almost negligible.  Typically, the stuns are used when the mobs attention has shifted to other than the main tank due to  a rogue backstabbing or an over-enthusiastic caster , lol.  That 18 seconds is enough for the tank to get a few good whacks and taunts in and get the mobs attention back where it belongs.  It certainly is more mana efficient than an extra heal for that rogue or caster.  It is also useful for interupting a mob's casting.<br>  Also, know the zone you are fighting in!  Check EQ Atlas  for info on zone mobs and always have the appropriate  resist buffs on your tank and puller. That resisted DOT spell is one less cure or heal spell you have to cast.  Speaking of casting mobs, probably the worst ones for a cleric to deal with are the ones who will dispel your tank or puller. Nothing is more frustrating than having to recast your buffs and symbols cause some mob decided to cast cancel magic 3 times in a row, lol. Unless you are in a raid-type scenario, your tank and puller won't have all 18 buff slots filled up,  so to prevent dispelling of the important ones, I usually cast a "filler buff" or two.  As a cleric of Brell Serilis, I have a neckpiece which has the clickable effect of casting strengthen, this stacks with the Shaman line of Strength spells and so, after all buffing has been done, I'll toss that on both tank and puller.  That way if they get hit with a dispel, the no-mana buff gets taken and not something important.  <br>  Ok, now for some specifics, I always have 2 heal spells memorized, one large one for the tank, one smaller one for the lower hp members , such as your casters.  When I get higher in level, there will be a third spell slot for my heal over time spell line. Usually two stun spells memmed as the dmg dealers in the group will do more dmg to that mob during the stun than any dd spell I could cast.  So, if the mob runs, 1 stun spell and the melees get 18 sec of free hits to the back of the mob, not too many survive to run after that.  Next is a cure spell as most higher dungeons will have nasty DOT casting mobs. Depending on where I am,  I will memm poison or disease cure, although some zones you need both.  The final 2 to 3 slots are personal choice, I prefer main resist buff and a hp/ac buff (which can also work as an emergency heal on your casters).<br>   Well, I think that about covers all I have to say and I welcome any and all comments and/or criticsm as only an idiot thinks he knows everything. Safe Journeys!<br><br>Brelgarian Stoutbrew<br>24 level dwarf cleric<br>Brell Serilis server<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
