<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100503668031493></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100503668031493><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=5410&mid=100503668031493>General</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=5410&mid=100503668031493#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=46685><span id=Scholar>Laleldil</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>72 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Nov 6th 3:51 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Not that I am a great and noble cleric, hence the surname of Tremulous, I have had a little experience with groups particularly in Karnor's Castle and the Captain's Room.  Up to this pointI have had little need to learn of other's effect on aggo, but I have notice it particularly important in this arena of development.<br><br>I am just now getting the sense that complete healing is a good spell to have. Up to this point Celestial Healing has pretty much healed even the mightiest of warriors.  With the warriors now becoming larger than celestial healing's heals, I learned I want a warrior, and usually a particular warrior to have the aggro at all times.  If someone other than that warrior is pulling I ask all others to let those two go toe to toe until they can begin their assault and not pull aggro from the warrior.  Should they get aggroed I ask for them to stop hitting and lose aggro to the warrior.<br><br>Same way with my enchanter/ess or bard.  I ask that they also try not to get the aggro, snaring, slowing, and other spells should be treated much the same way as a wizard's line of direct damage spells.  Snaring is not needed, at least in Captain's room, until later in a fight anyway, at least as it pertains to his running away.  If it is pertaining to our escaping, lets just say we don't normally run away at the start of the fight.<br><br>Tash, slow and other enchanter spells I would like to see occurring at seven eights of a mob's health, giving the warrior a full one eighth for of the mob's attention.<br><br>Not sure if this is the best way but I have two stuns and a root memmed just for enchanter protection.  I also have 4 heals memmed.  Complete heal so far as not gotten aggro on me.  Superior heals seem to supply more aggro even though the reciever might not be over healed.  Celestial healing also seems to provide little aggro for me.  Greater healing provides almost as much aggro as superior healing when it is used for the rangers and casters of the group when they start getting aggro.<br><br>The few times I have successfully pulled aggo from the bard I was casting greater healing in chain casts, swinging my silly little weapon, and nearly p!ssing in his boots.  I did get the aggro of one that soon got me to two bubbles of health when I began to drag it with me to the zone.  A back hit and another greater heal returned his attention to me and I started my slow little self to the zone.  I managed to get the mob that had returned to the passing bard by pausing just long enough to hit it in the back.  The bard escaped with 27 hp and I had a quarter bubble of life left and no mana for even a greater heal left.  I did not use DA because I wanted as much aggro from any and all of them that I could get as I was pulling them away from the melee type that I could no longer heal anyway.<br><br>I doubt that this was the best way to do things but that is what I tried.<br><br>Laleldil Tremulous<br>Tholuxe Paells<br>&nbsp;<br>A simple cleric of Rodcet Nif on Tholuxe Paells</td></tr>
